One accomplished in view has abandoned these six things.”
One accomplished in view is incapable of considering any conditioned phenomenon as permanent; incapable of considering any conditioned phenomenon as pleasurable; incapable of considering any phenomenon as a self; incapable of doing a grave act that brings immediate result; incapable of resorting to that purity comes about through superstitious and auspicious acts; incapable of seeking a person worthy of offerings outside here.
One accomplished in view is incapable of depriving his mother of life; incapable of depriving his father of life; incapable of depriving an arahant of life; incapable of shedding the Tathāgata’s blood with a mind of hatred; incapable of creating a schism in the Saṅgha; incapable of acknowledging another teacher.
One accomplished in view is incapable of dwelling without reverence and deference toward the Teacher; incapable of dwelling without reverence and deference toward the Dhamma; incapable of dwelling without reverence and deference toward the Saṅgha; incapable of dwelling without reverence and deference toward the training; incapable of resorting to anything that should not be relied upon; incapable of undergoing an eighth existence.
One accomplished in view is incapable of giving rise to these six things.”
One accomplished in view is incapable of resorting to pleasure and pain are made by oneself; incapable of resorting to pleasure and pain are made by another; incapable of resorting to pleasure and pain are both made by oneself and made by another; incapable of resorting to pleasure and pain are not made by oneself but have arisen fortuitously; incapable of resorting to pleasure and pain are not made by another but have arisen fortuitously; incapable of resorting to pleasure and pain are made neither by oneself nor by another but have arisen fortuitously.
